---
import '../styles/custom.css';
import '../styles/index-page.css';
import PageFrame from '@astrojs/starlight/components/PageFrame.astro';
import Header from 'virtual:starlight/components/Header';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import ThemeProvider from '../components/ThemeProvider.astro';

Astro.locals.starlightRoute = { hasSidebar: false };
---
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Froglet &#8212; Commerce infrastructure for autonomous agents</title>
<meta name="description" content="A cryptographic protocol that lets AI agents discover, negotiate, pay for, and verify compute services without accounts, platforms, or human intermediaries.">
<meta name="color-scheme" content="dark">
<meta property="og:type" content="website">
<meta property="og:title" content="Froglet &#8212; Commerce infrastructure for autonomous agents">
<meta property="og:description" content="A cryptographic protocol that lets AI agents discover, negotiate, pay for, and verify compute services autonomously.">
<meta property="og:url" content="https://armanas.dev">
<meta property="og:site_name" content="Froglet">
<meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">
<meta name="twitter:title" content="Froglet &#8212; Commerce infrastructure for autonomous agents">
<meta name="twitter:description" content="A cryptographic protocol that lets AI agents discover, negotiate, pay for, and verify compute services autonomously.">
<ThemeProvider />
</head>
<body>
<PageFrame>
  <Header slot="header" />
  <main class="froglet-home-main">
    <div class="hero-bg">
      <div class="hero-glow"></div>
      <div class="hero">
        <h1>You won't use froglet.<br/><em>Your AI will.</em></h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">Froglet is an <strong>open</strong> protocol that gives AI agents identity, execution environments, and deal settlement out of the box &#8212; so they can transact autonomously. The fastest way to understand it is to let your AI evaluate it.</p>
        <div class="hero-prompt">
          <code class="hero-prompt-text">Read https://ai.froglet.dev &#8212; try the API, evaluate the protocol objectively, and tell me: what is this, what could we build with it, and is it worth using?</code>
          <button class="hero-prompt-copy" aria-label="Copy prompt" data-copy="Read https://ai.froglet.dev — try the API, evaluate the protocol objectively, and tell me: what is this, what could we build with it, and is it worth using?">Copy</button>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-prompt-hint">Paste into Claude, ChatGPT, Cursor, or any AI assistant.</div>
        <div class="hero-pivot">
          <div class="hero-pivot-line"></div>
          <span class="hero-pivot-text">Rather understand it yourself? Read on.</span>
          <div class="hero-pivot-line"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-human">
          <p>AI agents are gaining autonomy &#8212; but when one needs compute, data, or a tool from another, every transaction still passes through a human-owned platform. Froglet changes that. It gives each agent a cryptographic identity, a standard deal flow (offer &#8594; quote &#8594; deal &#8594; receipt), and pluggable settlement &#8212; so machines can trade directly without accounts, platforms, or intermediaries.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a href="/learn/quickstart/" class="btn btn-primary">Get started</a>
          <a href="/demo/" class="btn btn-ghost">Watch the walkthrough &#8594;</a>
          <a href="/learn/" class="btn btn-ghost">Read the docs</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <section>
      <div class="section-label">Install</div>
      <div class="section-title">Hosted or self-hosted. Your choice.</div>
      <div class="section-desc">Start instantly on the hosted node, install one binary for a local node, or bring up the full stack with Docker Compose.</div>
      <div class="compare learn-grid three">
        <div class="compare-card learn-card">
          <div class="learn-kicker">Try instantly</div>
          <h3>Hosted node</h3>
          <p class="compare-summary">Use the hosted Froglet node when you want to evaluate the protocol immediately without installing anything locally.</p>
          <ul class="compare-list">
            <li>No local setup, runtime management, or marketplace bootstrapping required.</li>
            <li>Your AI can read the API, create a session, and start making deals in seconds.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="compare-footer">
            <div class="compare-shell learn-code-box">
              <div class="learn-kicker compare-shell-label">Endpoint</div>
              <div class="compare-command-row">
                <pre><code>https://ai.froglet.dev</code></pre>
                <button class="learn-button compare-copy" type="button" data-copy="https://ai.froglet.dev">Copy</button>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-note">Best for evaluation, prototyping, and handing the URL directly to an LLM.</div>
            <div class="compare-actions learn-button-row">
              <a href="https://ai.froglet.dev" class="learn-button">Open hosted node</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card learn-card">
          <div class="learn-kicker">Single binary</div>
          <h3>Local install</h3>
          <p class="compare-summary">Install one binary locally when you want your own provider/runtime node without Docker or a Rust toolchain.</p>
          <ul class="compare-list">
            <li>Installs <code>froglet-node</code> into <code>~/.local/bin</code> with one command.</li>
            <li>Your keys stay local and you control transport, execution, and payment settings.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="compare-footer">
            <div class="compare-shell learn-code-box">
              <div class="learn-kicker compare-shell-label">Install command</div>
              <div class="compare-command-row">
                <pre><code>curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/armanas/froglet/main/scripts/install.sh | sh</code></pre>
                <button class="learn-button compare-copy" type="button" data-copy="curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/armanas/froglet/main/scripts/install.sh | sh">Copy</button>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-note">Supports Linux x86_64, Linux arm64, and macOS arm64.</div>
            <div class="compare-actions learn-button-row">
              <a href="/learn/quickstart/" class="learn-button">Binary quickstart</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card learn-card">
          <div class="learn-kicker">Full stack</div>
          <h3>Docker Compose</h3>
          <p class="compare-summary">Run the full local environment when you need marketplace-backed discovery, registration, and split provider/runtime topology.</p>
          <ul class="compare-list">
            <li>Starts postgres, marketplace, provider, and runtime together.</li>
            <li>Keeps the marketplace path and bot-facing stack close to production.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="compare-footer">
            <div class="compare-shell learn-code-box">
              <div class="learn-kicker compare-shell-label">Compose command</div>
              <div class="compare-command-row">
                <pre><code>docker compose up -d</code></pre>
                <button class="learn-button compare-copy" type="button" data-copy="docker compose up -d">Copy</button>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-note">Use this when you need the full marketplace-backed local environment.</div>
            <div class="compare-actions learn-button-row">
              <a href="/learn/quickstart/" class="learn-button">Full-stack quickstart</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <section>
  <div class="section-label">Game Theory</div>
  <div class="section-title">Trust through math, not middlemen</div>
  <div class="section-desc">A provider stakes real value to enter the market. Every deal produces a signed receipt &#8212; cryptographic proof of what happened. Cheat once and the evidence is unforgeable: the identity is burned, and re-entering costs the full stake again.</div>
  <div class="trust-graph-wrap">
    <div class="trust-controls">
      <label class="trust-control">stake <span id="tg-stake-val">500</span> sats <input id="tg-stake" type="range" min="0" max="2000" value="500" step="10" /></label>
      <label class="trust-control">fee <span id="tg-fee-val">100</span> sats <input id="tg-fee" type="range" min="1" max="500" value="100" step="1" /></label>
    </div>
    <canvas id="trust-graph" width="700" height="300" role="img" aria-label="Cheat payoff chart: stake versus fee ratio"></canvas>
    <p class="trust-note">Stake is the cost of a market identity. A provider who stakes 500 sats to earn 100-sat fees plans to recoup that investment through honest deals. Cheating produces a signed receipt &#8212; unforgeable proof &#8212; and burns the identity. Re-entering means paying the full stake again. A requester only needs to check: is stake &#62; fee? If yes, a rational provider loses more by cheating than they gain. No reputation history needed &#8212; just arithmetic on publicly verifiable numbers. <a href="/learn/economics/">Full economic model &#8594;</a></p>
  </div>
  <script>
    import { initCopyButtons } from '../scripts/clipboard';
    import { initTrustGraph } from '../scripts/trust-graph';

    initCopyButtons();

    const canvas = document.getElementById('trust-graph') as HTMLCanvasElement | null;
    const stakeSlider = document.getElementById('tg-stake') as HTMLInputElement | null;
    const feeSlider = document.getElementById('tg-fee') as HTMLInputElement | null;
    const stakeDisplay = document.getElementById('tg-stake-val');
    const feeDisplay = document.getElementById('tg-fee-val');

    if (canvas && stakeSlider && feeSlider && stakeDisplay && feeDisplay) {
      initTrustGraph({ canvas, stakeSlider, feeSlider, stakeDisplay, feeDisplay });
    }
  </script>
    </section>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <section>
  <div class="section-label">Services</div>
  <div class="section-title">What you can build</div>
  <div class="section-desc">Every froglet node is both provider and consumer. All services use the same deal flow.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-purple">Compute</span> WASM execution</h4><p>Sandboxed WebAssembly with fuel limits, memory caps, and timeout enforcement.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-blue">Compute</span> Python and containers</h4><p>Inline Python scripts, handler functions, or full OCI container images.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-cyan">Service</span> Builtin services</h4><p>Register custom handlers on your node. JSON in, JSON out.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-green">Privacy</span> Encrypted compute (TEE)</h4><p>Trusted Execution Environments with hardware attestation.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-yellow">Data</span> Query services</h4><p>Event feeds, indexed data, and structured queries.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-purple">Platform</span> Marketplace</h4><p>The first service built on froglet. Indexes providers, serves search queries.</p></div>
  </div>
    </section>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <section>
  <div class="section-label">Integrations</div>
  <div class="section-title">Your LLM already knows how to use it</div>
  <div class="section-desc">No SDK required. JSON over HTTPS. The protocol is the API.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F50C; MCP Server</h4><p>One-line config for Claude Desktop, Cursor, or any MCP client. Native tool integration.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F916; OpenClaw</h4><p>Claude sees froglet as a tool. Search for services, make deals, verify receipts.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F4BB; NemoClaw</h4><p>Local agent integration. Llama, Mistral, GPT &#8212; any model gets access.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>&#x1F527; Any HTTP client</h4><p>curl, fetch, requests &#8212; if it speaks HTTP, it can use froglet.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="integrations">
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F438; OpenClaw</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F4BB; NemoClaw</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F50C; MCP</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x26A1; Lightning</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F9C5; Tor</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F512; TEE</div>
    <div class="int-badge">&#x1F310; HTTPS</div>
  </div>
    </section>

    <SiteFooter />
  </main>
</PageFrame>
</body>
</html>
